It appears there is a concurrent write in [`setParentContext`](https://github.com/junit-team/junit-framework/blob/4d034a78bb64f870c1236457c3a50b79155da00b/junit-platform-engine/src/main/java/org/junit/platform/engine/support/hierarchical/NodeTestTask.java#L101) with a concurrent read in [`prepare`](https://github.com/junit-team/junit-framework/blob/4d034a78bb64f870c1236457c3a50b79155da00b/junit-platform-engine/src/main/java/org/junit/platform/engine/support/hierarchical/NodeTestTask.java#L144).
```java
class NodeTestTask {

  private @Nullable C parentContext;

  private @Nullable C context;

  private void prepare() {
    requiredThrowableCollector().execute(() -> context = node.prepare(requireNonNull(parentContext)));
    parentContext = null;
  }

  void setParentContext(@Nullable C parentContext) {
    this.parentContext = parentContext;
  }

}
```

## Potential Solution

Marking the `parentContext` field `volatile` within `NodeTestTask` fixes the warning.

I hope this information is helpful for investigating the issue.

## Context

 - Used versions (Jupiter/Vintage/Platform):
   - Jupiter: 6.0.1
   - Platform: 6.0.1
 - OS: Linux

## Deliverables

This issue stems from #5296 which was closed because the report in question was being generated by Gradle, but the same issue exists in JUnit 6.0.3.

If you have a test using `@ParameterizedClass` and get it to generate legacy reports, the parameters do not appear in the report and you just get lots of duplicate entries for each method.  This makes it hard to tell which parameters failed and hard for other tools to process the report.

## Steps to reproduce

I used the `junit-platform-console-standalone-6.0.3.jar` to run the test from the command-line

The test was:

```java
